                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d298">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">763.72119/9354a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">Commission to Negotiate Peace</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-12-06T21:00:00-05:00"
                            >December 6, 1918—9 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>135. Russian Ambassador has sailed for Paris and Prince
                        <persName>Lvoff</persName>
                    <note n="2" xml:id="d298fn2">Prince <persName>George E. Lvoff</persName>,
                        Russian President of the Council of Ministers from March to July,
                        1917.</note> is leaving today for England. Both are concerned over the
                    question of the Russian representative at the Peace Conference. Their suggestion
                    is that the diplomatic representatives of the old Miliukov Government and
                    permanent [<hi rend="italic">prominent?</hi>] Russians such as
                        <persName>Lvoff</persName> should be invited. Department said matter would
                    be settled in Paris.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_PFL1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Polk</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
